I've had this issue too but it's in a project so complicated I wouldn't be able to extract a broken example easily. Even without an example though as a rule of thumb the User model should never be instantiated at import and this has been the case since custom user models were implemented. The following example allows backwards compatibility (originally taken from django-cms before they dropped support for older versions of Django) and allows you to use get_user_model() throughout:

    if django.VERSION >= (1, 5):
        from django.contrib.auth import get_user_model
    else:
        from django.contrib.auth.models import User
        User.USERNAME_FIELD = 'username'
        get_user_model = lambda: User

