@joshrsmith 
Using a testing framework is always a dependency. In the software world people are not afraid of depending on testing frameworks for increased productivity. For many languages there is a de-facto standard framework to use for testing. If a project chooses to use VUnit then it will have to accept that it is a dependency. VUnit will make it easier for multiple designers to collaborate on shared modules since it unifies things that might otherwise be fragmented. VUnit also makes it easy to quickly use other libraries in your test benches. In commercial projects where I have used VUnit it has been either a git submodule in the project repository or checked in along with the code.

If you for some reason do wish to have a shallow dependency on VUnit you can refrain from using anything more than test_runner_setup/test_runner_cleanup and then provide dummy implementations of those in a single package that can be used to run the test bench outside of VUnit.

I'm using the following filter to achieve this. It redacts more than just the sensitive KMS data, but it may be a useful starting point for others:

```python
def redact_kms_logs(record: logging.LogRecord):
    "Redact the plaintext entries in KMS log records."
    if record.levelno > logging.DEBUG:
        return 1
    if 'body' in record.msg or 'headers' in record.msg:
        if isinstance(record.args, tuple):
            record.args = ('REDACTED',) * len(record.args)
        elif isinstance(record.args, dict):
            record.args = {key: 'REDACTED' for key in record.args}
        else:
            record.args = 'REDACTED'
    return 1


logging.getLogger('botocore.parsers').addFilter(redact_kms_logs)
```

