![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3602335/24646879/cba0b2bc-191d-11e7-98b2-91f74c092cc6.png)

I only enabled the color and depth stream (as it it not posible to use the other due to being not native streams)

mRsDevice->enable_stream(rs::stream::depth, 640, 480, rs::format::z16, 60);
mRsDevice->enable_stream(rs::stream::color, 640, 480, rs::format::rgb8, 60);

I get the intrinsics of the depth.

mRsDepthIntrinsic = new rs::intrinsics();
auto tempDepthIntrinsic = mRsDevice->get_stream_intrinsics(rs::stream::depth);
memcpy(mRsDepthIntrinsic, &tempDepthIntrinsic, sizeof(rs::intrinsics));

Then for each frame I get both depth and color

cv::cvtColor(cv::Mat(mRsColorIntrinsic->height, mRsColorIntrinsic->width, CV_8UC3, (uchar*)mRsDevice->get_frame_data(rs::stream::color_aligned_to_depth)), mLastRGB, CV_RGB2BGR);		
mLastDepth = cv::Mat(mRsDepthIntrinsic->height, mRsDepthIntrinsic->width, CV_16U, (uchar*) mRsDevice->get_frame_data(rs::stream::depth));

and finally pixels in color and depth are completely aligned so for each (X,Y) in color image you can directly take the (X,Y) on the depth and deproject using the intrinsic matrix of the depth.

